Discovered_Entry: Small bottom-feeding and docile. Protects itself from predation by local otters with its many sharp spines

Unseen_Entry: Small, travels in groups in dense foliage
Discovered_Entry: Small scavengers, feed off of scraps found in and around the sea floor. Takes shelter in dense foliage to avoid predation

Unseen_Entry: Medium sized, agile, found near areas with high urchin population
Discovered_Entry: Their lean, smooth bodies allow for fast and deft movement between kelp growths. Independent by nature, but are innately curious and mate for life

Unseen_Entry: Large and slow, found in clearings
Discovered_Entry: Due to their size, rays see very little threat from predators. Which explains their almost comically relaxed nature.

Unseen_Entry: Rare, well camoflaged, and highly intelligent
Discovered_Entry: Shy and well camoflaged, very few individuals have ever been seen. Reports frequently indicate cognitive abilities almost comparable to our own.
